            "id": "321292357ddb4e9c9453f",
            "questionText": "A space exploration company is planning a mission to Mars and wants to place a satellite into a stable circular orbit. The satellite has a mass of $!$m = 500\\,\\text{kg}$!$, and the intended orbital altitude above the Martian surface is $!$h = 500\\,\\text{km}$!$. Mars has a mass of $!$M = 6.39 \\times 10^{23}\\,\\text{kg}$!$ and a radius of $!$R = 3389.5\\,\\text{km}$!$. Determine the total energy required to place this satellite into the specified orbit around Mars.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "301acb8c7e9a440d917bc",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by finding the orbital radius at which the satellite will orbit Mars. Identify the correct expression that relates the orbital radius to the radius of Mars and the altitude of the satellite.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = R + h$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = R - h$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = h - R$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "d4944f8e5030410888300",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now that you understand how to find the orbital radius, determine which formula is used to compute the total mechanical energy of a satellite in a circular orbit around a massive body.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ea1e89e6-51eb-4c26-9db9-4af747efca26"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E = -\\frac{GMm}{2r}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E = -\\frac{GMm}{r}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E = \\frac{GMm}{2r}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "25d76e98def241ad98dff",
                    "stepText": "Now, proceed to compute the product of the universal gravitational constant $!$G$!$ and the mass of Mars $!$M$!$. Use the values $!$G = 6.674\\times10^{-11}\\,\\text{m}^3/\\text{kg}\\,\\text{s}^2$!$ and $!$M = 6.39\\times10^{23}\\,\\text{kg}$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "4.266e13"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m^3/s^2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "913f94ce-32fd-4e0b-81d1-2d6512bc5085"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "d5bfc07fa9264f9a943f6",
                    "stepText": "Excellent. Next, calculate the numerator of the energy expression by multiplying the product $!$GM$!$ from the previous step by the satellite's mass $!$m = 500\\,\\text{kg}$!$. What do you obtain?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2.133e16"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg\u00b7m^3/s^2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "913f94ce-32fd-4e0b-81d1-2d6512bc5085"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "3d4e0e6a37d24056b8a30",
                    "stepText": "To continue, determine the denominator of the energy formula by finding twice the orbital radius. Recall that the orbital radius was computed earlier. What is the value of $!$2r$!$?",
