        {
            "id": "dd7ffff3fedb486caabe5",
            "questionText": "A team of astronomers has discovered a new dwarf planet in the outer reaches of our solar system. The dwarf planet orbits the Sun with a semi-major axis of $!$a = 8.0 \\times 10^{12}\\,\\text{m}$!$ and an orbital period of $!$T = 600\\,\\text{years}$!$ (with 1 year equal to $!$3.154 \\times 10^7\\,\\text{seconds}$!$). Given that the dwarf planet's mass is $!$m = 5.0 \\times 10^{22}\\,\\text{kg}$!$, first use Kepler's Third Law to estimate the mass of the Sun, and then calculate the gravitational force between the Sun and the dwarf planet. (Provide the final numerical value for the gravitational force.)",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "c0241753dfe44ffcbe361",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by converting the orbital period from years to seconds. Identify the correct conversion relation that you would use to convert $!$600\\,\\text{years}$!$ into seconds.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T_{s} = 600 \\times 3.154 \\times 10^7$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T_{s} = \\frac{600}{3.154 \\times 10^7}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T_{s} = 600 + 3.154 \\times 10^7$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "ebbe481a2220489eb9a47",
                    "stepText": "Now, let\u2019s determine the relation given by Kepler's Third Law that connects the gravitational parameter $!$GM$!$ with the semi-major axis $!$a$!$ and the orbital period $!$T$!$. Please select the correct formula.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "743c1657-ccbf-4c07-9271-689fe01f8ba9",
                        "fbd8edf3-8814-4fd4-a0d3-e99cc717d126"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$GM = \\frac{4\\pi^2a^3}{T^2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$GM = \\frac{T^2a^3}{4\\pi^2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$GM = \\frac{a^3}{T^2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "fed64f5728e2420aa8ad4",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that you have converted the time and identified the relation, calculate the mass of the Sun using the established relation with the values for $!$a$!$ and the orbital period in seconds. Provide the numerical value you obtain.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
